senthal shows that when Victorians discussed the moral dimensions of reading novels, they were also subtly discussing the genre’s formal properties.For most, Victorian moralizing is one of the period’s least attractive and interesting qualities. But Good Form argues that the moral interpretation of novel experience was essential in the development of the novel form—and that this moral approach is still a fundamental, if unrecognized, part of how we understand novels. Bringing together ideas from philosophy, literary history, and narrative theory, Rosenthal shows that we cannot understand the formal principles of the novel that we have inherited from the nineteenth century without also understanding the moral principles that have come with them. Good Form helps us to understand the way Victorians read, but it also helps us to understand the way we read now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEthics in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aAnalogy.  aAnecdote.  aAutobiography.  aBackstory.  aBildungsroman.  aCambridge University Press.  aCharacter (arts).  aCharles Dickens.  aConscience.  aConsciousness.  aCrime fiction.  aCriticism.  aCritique of Pure Reason.  aD. A. Miller.  aDaniel Deronda.  aDeus ex machina.  aE. M. Forster.  aEdward Bulwer-Lytton.  aElizabeth Gaskell.  aEpic poetry.  aEthics.  aEugene Aram.  aExplanation.  aFiction.  aFranco Moretti.  aFredric Jameson.  aGenre fiction.  aGenre.  aGeorge Eliot.  aGeorge Meredith.  aGood and evil.  aGroundwork of the Metaphysic of Morals.  aGwendolen Harleth.  aGwendolen.  aHalpern.  aHistorical fiction.  aHumour.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIan Watt.  aIllustration.  aIntuitionism.  aJack Sheppard.  aJames Cle